  "prompt": "What are the best ways to cook winkles?",
  "response": "Cooking winkles is quite simple and can be a delightful way to enjoy these small sea snails. Here's a basic method along with some variations you might enjoy:\n\n### Basic Preparation\n1. **Cleaning:** Rinse the winkles under cold water to remove any sand or debris. Some people prefer to soak them in salt water for a few hours to help the winkles purify themselves, but this step is optional.\n2. **Boiling:** Place the cleaned winkles in a pot of salted boiling water. You may also add a bay leaf or two for extra flavor.\n3. **Cooking Time:** Boil the winkles for about 3-5 minutes. Overcooking can make them tough, so keep an eye on the time.\n4. **Draining:** Once cooked, drain the winkles in a colander and let them cool until they are warm enough to handle.\n\n### Serving Suggestions\n- **Traditional:** Serve them with pins or toothpicks to help pull the meat out of the shell. Enjoy them plain or with melted butter, vinegar, or a squeeze of lemon juice.\n- **Garlic Butter:** Melt some butter in a pan, add a few cloves of minced garlic, and toss the cooked winkles in the mixture for a flavorful twist.\n- **Herbs and Wine:** After boiling and draining, saut\u00e9 the winkles with white wine, parsley, and garlic for a Mediterranean flair.\n- **Spicy Option:** Add a pinch of cayenne pepper or some chopped chili to melted butter or oil, toss the winkles in, and serve.\n\n### Tips\n- It can be helpful to use a pin or specialized seafood fork to remove the meat from the shell.\n- Discard any winkles that do not open during cooking, as this could indicate that they were dead before cooking and may not be safe to eat.\n\nThese methods and variations highlight the simplicity and versatility of cooking winkles, allowing you to experiment with different flavors and find your preferred taste.",
